# How This DevOps Project Works & What to Configure

## How It Works (End-to-End Flow)

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  1. TERRAFORM (you run once)                                                     │
│     Creates: VPC → 2 public + 2 private subnets, IGW, NAT, route tables          │
│              EKS cluster + node group in private subnets                          │
│              Optionally: Route53 zone + A record to ALB                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  2. YOU CONFIGURE KUBECTL                                                         │
│     aws eks update-kubeconfig --region <region> --name <cluster-name>             │
│     (Cluster name = project_name + "-" + environment + "-eks", e.g. lms-devops-dev-eks) │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  3. AWS LOAD BALANCER CONTROLLER (you install on EKS once)                        │
│     Watches Ingress resources and creates an Application Load Balancer (ALB)      │
│     in AWS. Without this, the Ingress manifest does nothing.                     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  4. DEPLOY APPS (Helm or kubectl)                                                │
│     Each microservice: Deployment + Service + ConfigMap + Secret                 │
│     Services: api-gateway, user-service, product-service (ClusterIP)             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  5. APPLY INGRESS                                                                │
│     kubectl apply -f kubernetes/ingress.yaml                                      │
│     AWS LB Controller creates ALB; routes /api, /users, /products to services   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  6. JENKINS (optional CI/CD)                                                      │
│     On each run: Checkout from GitHub → Build 3 Docker images → Push to Docker Hub│
│     → Update kubeconfig for EKS → Helm upgrade --install each service            │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                        │
                                        ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  7. ROUTE53 (optional)                                                           │
│     After ALB exists: set alb_dns_name + alb_zone_id in Terraform → apply        │
│     Creates A record (e.g. app.example.com → ALB)                                 │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Summary:** Terraform provisions the network and EKS. You configure kubectl and install the AWS LB Controller. You deploy the three microservices (Helm or manifests) and apply the Ingress so the ALB is created. Jenkins can automate build-and-deploy. Route53 optionally points your domain at the ALB.

